At 18:03 -0800 29.12.1998, Rafael Kitover wrote:
>According to a recent discussion on this list, yes. Consider the
>following:
>
>/def -F -ag -msimple -t'Caelum tests' foo = \
>  /def -F -p2 -n1 -mglob -t'*' bar = \
>    /if ({*} =~ "") \
>      /def -p1 -n1 -ag -msimple -t'' baz%%;\
>    /endif
>
>'bar' and 'baz' essentially operate on the same line, due to 'bar' having
>a higher priority and being fallthrough. So it checks if the line is
>empty, and if so automatically generates a gag to remove it.

On these occasions I use a different approach:

Define two triggers when we get the test line, first one will gag empty
lines and the second will remove triggers if we didn't get an empty line

/def -F -ag -msimple -t'Caelum tests' foo = \
  /def -p2 -n1 -ag -msimple -t'' foo_gag%; \
  /def -F -p1 -n1 -mglob -t'*' foo_undef = /purge -msimple foo_gag

This will work ofcourse - maybe a faster alternative is (if purge is faster
than a glob match and -n1):

/def -F -ag -msimple -t'Caelum tests' foo = \
  /def -p2 -n1 -ag -msimple -t'' foo_gag = /purge -msimple foo_undef%; \
  /def -F -p1 -n1 -mglob -t'*' foo_undef = /purge -msimple foo_gag

Notice however, that we cannot make the first macro fall-thru, even if it
didn't matter in our case for there might be some other lower priority
trigger triggering and doing things to empty lines.

Anyways, the speed difference between these is minimal and doesn't matter.

