In the past, key (PgUp/PgDn) and/or scrollbar style scrollback in tf
was not very important, since tf's own /recall command provided a
richer (though more complex) way of accessing the same text, and many
users (most importantly, myself) run tf inside another application
(like xterm) that provides one or both types of scrollback.

However, the new virtual window features in 5.0 (still a long way from
release) will turn the buffers of those applications to spaghetti.  So,
5.0 will probably have key style scrollback built in.  Don't worry,
/recall will still be available; both methods of viewing old text are
useful in different situations.

Instead of waiting for the flood of questions about "virtual window
features", I'll just explain here:  5.0 already has a separate virtual
window per world connection, similar to Screen's windows or linux's
virtual consoles except that the input window (in visual mode) doesn't
change.  I am also considering adding the ability to have multiple
visible output windows with different (or the same) world connections
displayed in each, and maybe even full terminal emulation.

