sure, here's mine:

/DEF -mregexp -h"PROMPT H:([0-9]*)/([0-9]*) S:([0-9]*)/([0-9]*)>" prompt_hook =\
 /test prompt({*}) %;\
 /SETENV hp=%P1%; /SETENV hpmax=%P2%; /SETENV sp=%P3%; /SETENV spmax=%P4

/SET status_fields= :1 "H:":2 hp:-4 "/":1 hpmax:4 :1 "S:":2 sp:-4 "/":1 spmax:4\
 :1 @active:2 :1 @log:5 :1 @more:8:Br :1 @world

The prompt_hook (hopefully) catches my prompt from an LP mud that doesn't send a
termination character, it works pretty well. I test the prompt, then grab the
numbers and stuff them into a few variables (my current and maximum hit points
and spell points). Grabbing them is done by a regular expression (regexp) match.

The status_fields line has a few labels, some nice formatting and uses the
variables I grabbed in my prompt hook. Looking at it from the left (the first
line) it has a space (:1) then a label "H:" (for hit points) that is 2
characters wide (:2) followed by my hp variable that is right justified and 4
characters long (hp:-4). Next is a slash to make things easier to read ("/":1)
that is one character wide. Then my maximum hit points (which can change due to
items, spells, etc) which is left justified (hpmax:4). Spell points are
displayed in the same manner.

The rest of the line is basically from the default, variables starting with @
refer to internal variables and show the activity status, log status, more
status and world connected to. They are pretty much from the default settings.

It looks something like:

_H:_924/924__S:_859/859___________________________________More 100_worldname

You can put more variables in it as needed (I use different status lines for
different characters and muds).

