On Sun, 17 Jan 1999 mikael@nydalah676.sn.umu.se wrote:
> How do I turn off or on triggers ?

You can use /ismacro for that purpose, I have a trigger to track a mobile
and walk in the directions my track tells me. I turn it on and off with
/track. Be aware of the fact that I define the macro within the body of
another macro, which means you have to use an % or $ extra ;) Read /help
substitution for more info. It's also used in speedwalk.tf.
 
/def track = \
    /if /ismacro doTrack%; /then \
        /echo -e %%% Autotracking disabled.%;\
        /undef doTrack%;\
    /else  \
        /echo -e %%% Autotracking enabled.%;\
        /def -mregexp -t"^You see your quarry's trail head \
        (east|west|north|south|down|up) from here!" doTrack = %%{P1} %;\
    /endif
/track

Another sollution would be to use a variable in a definition, like

/def loot = \
        /set looting $[!looting] %;\
        /if (looting) /echo %%% Now looting corpses %;\
        /else /echo %%% No longer looting corpses %;\
        /endif

/def -t"yourTriggerThing" = \
	/if (looting) \
		YourStuffToLootCorpses %;\
	/endif

You can now toggle with /loot.

Personally I prefer the first method because it keeps the trigger as fast
as possible, uses the /if command only when you toggle, doesnt use global
variables, and defines the trigger only when needed.

I think Gossamer had another thingie on her homepage to disable triggers
without ditching 'em.

