> PROBLEM is that /set doesnt accept trailing spaces, so "/col < blah blah"
> will do "<blahblah" with color codes. Can anyone help me ditching the
> first /set ?
> 
> /set colorList=|B| |C| |G| |R| |Y| |W| |P| |BK| |BB| |BC| |BG| |BR| |BY|
> |BW| |BP|
> 
> /def -i fillColorString = \
>         /set colorString $[strcat (colorString, $(/nth $[rand(1,15)] 
> %{colorList}), substr(inputLine, %{character}, 1))]
> 
> /def -i col = \
>         /let inputLine %* %;\
>         /set colorString $[substr(inputLine, 0, 1)] %;\
>         /for character 1 $[strlen({inputLine}) - 1] /fillColorString %;\
>         /send %{colorString}
> 
> Btw ditching the variables and/or obsolete definitions would be fine too
> ;p

It's not /set that loses spaces, it's macro syntax.  Use expresion syntax
to preserve spaces.  Try this:

/def rth = /echo %R

/set colorList=|B| |C| |G| |R| |Y| |W| |P| |BK| |BB| |BC| |BG| |BR| |BY| \
    |BW| |BP|

/def col = \
    /set dst=%; \
    /set i=$[strlen({-1})]%; \
    /while (i > 0) \
        /test dst:=strcat($$(/rth %%colorList), substr({-1}, --i, 1), dst)%; \
    /done%; \
    /send - %1 %dst

I also made some other minor improvements:
* Instead of calling strlen in every iteration of the loop, I call it once
  before the loop starts, and work backwards through the string.
* Combined /nth and rand() into /rth.

