A while back I had looked at using ssh for tunneling, but came to the
conclusion that it was undesireable to tie the MUD into the underlying 
authentication that ssh depends on.  MUD-over-ssh can be done easily, but
not without exposing any latent holes in your ssh server to the probing
and prodding of every user on your MUD.  In addition, it would take
some hacking to get an ssh-based solution that doesn't require root access
on the server end.  With the restrictions some countries place on crypto
export, you end up with a bit of a mess.

SSL provides a quick, and not at all dirty, general-purpose solution.  I
would be happy to work with anyone interested in laying out an ssh-based
solution, but I think there are assumptions in the ssh model which make
SSL a better overall choice.

