Typing away merrily, Marek Trebicki produced the immortal words:
> For example /bind ^S = say s suspended my tf (unix).
> Have to Ctrl + C. Anybody know why ?

This isn't tinyfugue.  This is the terminal settings for your tty (login
line).  At a shell, before starting tinyfugue, type "stty -a" - this
will list all the current settings.

^S is stop - a kind of flow control.  To resume, type ^Q - assuming
that you're using default settings.

You can disable this with:
$ stty stop '^-' start '^-'
(where '$ ' is the shell prompt) before starting tinyfugue.  Note that
the ^- there are two characters, a caret then a minus, not
control-minus.

> Further, there is an example after h bind
> 
> /bind ^Xtw = :jumps to the left; ...
> 
> Am I supposed to press all three keys (X, T and W)
> simultaneously?

As I understand it, ^X, then t, then w.

> Where are all keybindigns that are already workin (coded in tf)
> listed? I mean, sure /list -b lists only my bindings, where are
> othere, U know, like ^C, ^[p or whatever. Could anybody gimme

^C is also a tty setting - it sends an interrupt signal (SIGINT) to the
tinyfugue process.  Tinyfugue catches this and then asks you what you
want to do.

The normal bindings are defined with '-i', to be invisible unless you
explicitly ask to see them.  Use:
/list -ib
and you'll see all the bindings, not just the visible ones.  Use '-I' to
see only the invisible ones.  Use:
/help list
to see more information on the /list command.

