That would require capturing the incoming information from the MUD,
capturing the commands, timestamps on both, then feeding them in.
Whilst it may be just about possible, I doubt that it's a worthwhile
approach.

You can fiddle it a bit at present, provided you don't mind not being in
tinyfugue for the replay.  "/log -t" would be good, but provided you
don't want colour the following should work:
 * Increase %{histsize} to something large enough to handle _everything_
   from the MUD session.
 * At the end, after disconnecting, do:
    /log filename
    /recall -t%@: -q -wTheWorldName 1-
    /log off
 * To replay, run a script (shell, perl, whatever) over the log file
   which subtracts the time given in the stamp for the current line from
   that of the previous line, pauses for that length of time, then
   output's the line (without timestamp).

The "-t%@:" will use a timestamp format consisting of the system time in
seconds since Jan 1st 1970 (on Unix at least - it's documented in /help
ftime as "raw system time (nonstandard TF extension)") followed by a
colon, then the obligatory space.  So you get, eg, the two lines:
924344470:  You emote 'Comet huggles' to Erin.
924344491: > Queen Erin huggles rb
^^^^^^^^^^^
 timestamp

So display the first, then pause 21 seconds, then the next.  Perl is
probably going to be the most sensible option for this (no advocacy wars
please!)

It might be possible to get colours too, with tfio streams instead of /log
- I can't remember where the colour gets stripped and what might be
possible.  Sorry.

