Well, actually none of the answers were correct :) Normal screen 3.7.2
displays colors without a flaw. You don't need the +ansi version.

The screen displays colors if the term it is running on has color support
- and it determines it by looking at the termcap entry. So, if you pick
some term like vt220 or linux (console), it has color support and screen
shows colors.

The problem people are having is that the normal 'xterm' termcap or
terminfo doesn't advertise color support - the name of the xterm with
colors varies in different termcaps/infos. For example, debian linux
distribution has xterm-debian as the xterm with colors, RMS:s common
terminfo distribution has xterm-xfree86 as the term which has colors.
These shouldn't be mixed up with 'color-xterm' or 'xterm-color' or any of
the crappy xterm variants that exist.

The obvious solution is ofcourse that you bug your administrator into
putting a _correct_ xterm entry in the termcap/info. Or, if you are the
administrator yourself, go get xterm-93 package from somewhere which
normally comes with xfree86 (xc/programs/xterm), and configure it and say
make install-ti to install a good termcap entry which works fine.

Now, the solution offered here, something like this:
termcap  xterm 'AF=\E[3%dm:AB=\E[4%dm'
terminfo xterm 'AF=\E[3%p1%dm:AB=\E[4%p1%dm'
forcefully inserts color describing entries to the termcap/info database.

This is ofcourse fine, but I would still recommend bugging your admins to
fix things properly as this affects programs run outside screen (all
ncurses software for example).

