Lemme try and explain the status line. 

First you set the status_field variable, which consists of a number of
variable names, widths and an attributes. Just forget about the attribute
for a while.

Examples:

/set var=
/set status_fields=var:5
This gives a status line with 5 characters reserved for the contents of a
variable named 'var' The "/set var=" is necessary because the field name
must be declared before the status_field variable.

/set var=blah
The status line now displays blah_________ ...

/set var=blahblah
The status line now displays blahb____ ... because we only reserved 5
characters for the variable.

Now let's take a look at the original status line:
/set status_fields=@more:8:Br :1 @world :1 @read:6 :1 @active:11 :1
@log:5 :1 @mail:6 :1 insert:6 :1 @clock:5

The variables with a @ are special variables and described in the help
file. They use special format variables like status_int_more. Nothing to
be worried about if you want to stuff your own variables in it, just set a
variable and put its name literally in the status_fiels variable.

The " :1 " are fields without a variable, and they simply eat up 1
character of the status line, causing an empty space on it.

One example of an attribute is the "Br" behind the @more variable. It
causes the "More: 35" thing to be displayed bold and reversed. So if we'd
wanna display "blah" in bold and reverse, our line would be:

/set var=blah
/set status_fields=var:5:Br

For a list of all attributes, see /help attribute.

I don't know what the hassle in the help file about redrawing the status
line means, my status line changes at the same moment as a variable
changes. 

