You want the code inside that /repeat to execute when the timer expires,
not now, so you need to escape the %; -

/repeat -%ticksize 1 \
      /IF (_tick_act == 1) \
              do_something %%; \
              do_something else %%; \
              /set _tick_act=2 %%;\
      /ELSE \
              do_something %%; \
              do_something else %%; \
              /set _tick_act=1 %%;\
      /ENDIF %; \

If you make reference to any variables that you don't want to have evaluated
now (or any expressions with $[], or any commands with $(/ )), you should
escape those % (and $) also.

If you type /ps, you'll see the big /if ... /else ... code show up as the
command to execute.  To make this cleaner, you could also write a function
to do the same thing:

/def dotickstuff = \
    /if (_tick_act == 1) \
      blah blah %; \
    /else \
      etc...
    /endif

/repeat -%ticksize 1 /dotickstuff



