Try instead:
/def -PCgreen -mregexp -t'^The (.+) introduces (him|her)self as:$' get_desc =\
	/set descr=%P1 %; \
	/def -mregexp -n1 -p1000 -F -t'(*)' get_name = /set name=%%P1 %%; /undef
get_name

The things I did different:
Used parantheses in the regexp.  The way you did it it assumes it will be 4
words.  This may be safe, but using parens is more universal.  %P1 substitutes
to the first paren expression.
Added -p1000, this is just a high number to make sure this executes before
anything else.  The -F means other stuff (Hilites, partials, etc) still
trigger on it.
Escaped the % in the /def - Otherwise it would substitute in the 'The'.
Changed .*. to .+ (1 or more of any character)
Gave a name to the /def inside the get_desc one.
Had the get_name macro undefine itself.  Otherwise you'll have a bunch of *
triggers defined.

> Also, is there a way I can set up prompts like in shell, for example:
>         echo -n "What is your name? :"
>         read name

You can set a prompt with /prompt, and then read a line with the SEND hook,
having it /undef itself afterwards in a similar manner to get_name above.
