Which is good, except that you need a new macro for each new spell.

How about ...

/def -F -mregexp -t" utters the words '([^']+)'" match_magick = \
	/eval /substitute \
	%{PL} utters the words to invoke "%%{spellstr_%{P1}-?%{P1}?}"
/set spellstr_abrazak=flamedarts
/set spellstr_foo=bar
/set spellstr_funky=wibble!

The ([^']+) matches a sequence of at least one character that isn't a
single quote and, since it's the first parenthesised bit, makes %{P1}
refer to it.  (/help regexp  /help %Pn)

The /eval is bad.  I'm sure it's unnecessary with cleaner syntax, but
I'm at the end of the first in a run of night-shifts and am a little
tired.  ;^)  Anyway, it goes through the rest, evaluating it again.  The
%{P1} gets replaced with the spell-name, and the %% becomes % which hits
the eval as %{spellstr_abrakaz-???} which becomes flamedarts

The -?%{P1}? (from /help substitution, see %{selector-default})
provides a default if the variable isn't defined, so say you get:
PointyHatBloke utters the words 'MyNewSpell'
then you'll get:
PointyHatBloke utters the words to invoke "?MyNewSpell?" instead of
being left with a useless empty pair of quotes.

I vaguely recall that various sets of macros, eg David Moore's & Karen
Etheridge's, use tricks like this - you're effectively fiddling a set of
strings with well-defined names to behave like a hash.

Does this help?
